issue.body:
From Wikipedia (not the RFC but by this point one would hope it is representative), ISO8601 UTC date times (offset of zero) can be represented with:

>An offset of zero, in addition to having the special representation "Z", can also be stated numerically as "+00:00", "+0000", or "+00"

However, the ECMAScript5 spec states that date serialization is based on a subset of the ISO8601 standard with Z being used for UTC and +00:00 format being the only numeric format used for other zones.  

See:
https://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/5.1/#sec-15.9.1.15
https://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/5.1/#sec-15.9.5.43
https://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/5.1/#sec-15.9.5.44

This explains some of the confusion in
https://github.com/FasterXML/jackson-databind/issues/1624

And while UTC (offset zero) can be represented with the various "zero" forms according to ISO8601 and some browsers may correctly parse the full ISO8601 standard (I believe Chrome does), from a practical perspective browsers are still in use that only serialize UTC dates that have a Z and will fail with other zero offset formats.   This is one specific user-agent that I have on hand but I have seen others, that fail (IE 11?)
>Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux i686) AppleWebKit/534.34 (KHTML, like Gecko)

The preferred serialization format for UTC in Chrome.. as seen from the Chrome console
```
JSON.stringify(new Date)
""2018-12-13T05:38:43.273Z""
```

And for this reason we continue to use the deprecated ISO8601DateFormat.

```
    @Bean
    public ObjectMapper getObjectMapper() {
        ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper();
        // setup the ISO8601 output format with the trailing Z instead of hour difference to support Connect+
        // this is compatible with default Jackson Date deserialization
        mapper.registerModule(new JavaTimeModule());
        mapper.registerModule(new Jdk8Module());
        mapper.setTimeZone(TimeZone.getTimeZone("UTC"));
        SimpleModule module = new SimpleModule();
        module.addDeserializer(Locale.class, new LocaleDeserializer());
        module.addSerializer(Locale.class, new LocaleSerializer());
        mapper.registerModule(module);
        mapper.configure(SerializationFeature.WRITE_DATES_AS_TIMESTAMPS, false);
        mapper.setDateFormat(new ISO8601DateFormat());
        // enforce order of properties to provide consistent ETags
        mapper.configure(MapperFeature.SORT_PROPERTIES_ALPHABETICALLY, true);
        return mapper;
    }
```
It would be helpful to have some format whether it is the existing one, some particular configuration of the standard format, or something entirely new that makes the Z preferred when serializing a UTC date (something like EcmaScript5ISO8601Subset if it is not entirely accurate to call it ISO8601).

